<paragraph id="2A7836CB197F295C74C2FB76FECBFB28" blockId="47.[144,1103,1207,1366]" box="[144,265,1207,1231]" pageId="47" pageNumber="622">
<heading id="713081A7197F295C74C2FB76FECBFB28" box="[144,265,1207,1231]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="47" pageNumber="622" reason="5">
<emphasis id="18B3EAD9197F295C74C2FB76FECBFB28" box="[144,265,1207,1231]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="622">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A7836CB197F295C74C2FB1FFC7AFAB1" blockId="47.[144,1103,1207,1366]" pageId="47" pageNumber="622">
The specific epithet honours the ‘Guarani’, the name for an ethnic group of natives used here as a noun in apposition. Since the mid-1920s, for the Guarani subgroup Kaiowa, there has been a continuous process of expropriation of Guarani lands, which are constantly threatened by farmers (
<bibRefCitation id="4E564B3A197F295C76DFFAFFFC6AFAB1" author="Almeida RFT &amp; Mura F" box="[653,936,1342,1366]" pageId="47" pageNumber="622" pagination="11" refId="ref28720" refString="Almeida RFT, Mura F. 2003. Guarani-Kaiowa. Instituto Socioambiental, Povos Indigenas no Brasil [Internet]. [cited 2013 Apr 11]. Available from: http: // pib. socioambiental. org / en / povo / guarani-kaiowa / print." type="journal article" year="2003">Almeida and Mura 2003</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
